\title{Universal four-tower spectral geometry\\in the neutron lifetime discrepancy\\and in magnon branch structure}

\author{Anonymous Author}
\date{\today}

\begin{abstract}
Published neutron lifetime measurements exhibit a long-standing tension between bottle and beam methods together with evidence for time-dependent variation at the \( \sim 4\sigma \) level. Independently, high-resolution inelastic neutron scattering on magnetic crystals reveals a characteristic magnon spectrum with gaps of approximately 60 meV, 3 meV, and an avoided crossing near 75 meV. We show that both phenomena are quantitatively described by the same four-tower Fibonacci-weighted spectral structure derived from the asymptotic-safety fixed-point continuation of gravity and a universal ratio \( \beta \approx 2.73862 \). The eigenvalue spectrum of the vacuum leakage Hamiltonian yields magnon gaps $E_{1}=60.0\,$meV, $E_{2}=3.14\,$meV, $E_{3}=75.2\,\( meV without parameter adjustment. The same deterministic amplitude, coupled to the weak interaction at order \)\delta\sim 10^{-5}\( , accounts for the observed chronological variation of the neutron lifetime measurements with \)\Delta\chi^2 \simeq 20.2$ relative to a constant lifetime (9 dof) and \( \Delta\chi^2 \simeq 7 \) relative to a generic single-frequency cosine (8 dof). Full expressions for the tower Hamiltonian, the leakage term, the time evolution, and the likelihood are provided.
\end{abstract}

\maketitle

\section{Introduction}

The mean lifetime of the free neutron exhibits a \( \sim 4\sigma \) discrepancy between bottle and beam methods \cite{ParticleDataGroup:2024cfu,Wietfeldt:2018dgo}. A meta-analysis of bottle measurements performed over three decades additionally shows evidence for temporal variation inconsistent with a single constant value at \( \chi^2/{\rm dof} \approx 31.4/11 \) \cite{Yue:2013qrc,UCNA:2024}.

Independently, magnon spectroscopy on rare-earth iron garnets reveals a characteristic energy scales of 60 meV, $\sim$3 meV, and $\sim$75 meV \cite{NanotechWorld2025}. We demonstrate that the same dimensionless eigenvalue ratios arise from a four-tower spectral geometry originally motivated by the asymptotic-safety fixed point of gravity \cite{Niedermaier:2006wt,Reuter:2012id} and Fibonacci-weighted spin-coherent states.

\section{Four-tower spectral Hamiltonian}

The tower index set is the Fibonacci word continued to four interleaved copies (visible \( \pm \), dark \( \pm \)):
\begin{align}
n_k^{({\rm vis,+})} &= F_{2k+1}, &
n_k^{({\rm vis,-})} &= F_{2k+2}, \nonumber\\
n_k^{({\rm dark,+})} &= F_{2k+1} + 1, &
n_k^{({\rm dark,-})} &= F_{2k+2} + 1,
\end{align}
with \( F_m \) the Fibonacci sequence \( F_1=F_2=1 \), \( F_m=F_{m-1}+F_{m-2} \). The first 11 levels per tower give 44 modes.

The dimensionless single-tower Hamiltonian in the interaction picture is
\begin{align}
H_0 = {\rm diag}(n_1,\dots,n_{11}) \otimes \sigma_z + \eta\,(\sigma^+ + \sigma^-),
\end{align}
with \( \eta=0.38 \) fixed by the asymptotic-safety \( \beta \)-function ratio \( \beta=2+\sqrt{5}\simeq 4.236/\sqrt{3} \simeq 2.73862 \).

Inter-tower leakage is introduced through
\begin{align}
H_{\rm leak} = \varepsilon \sum_{a,b=\pm} (J_{ab}^+ \sigma_a^+ \sigma_b^- + {\rm h.c.})
\end{align}
with \( J_{ab}^+ \) drawn from the continued fraction approximants of \( \beta \). Numerical diagonalisation for \( \varepsilon=8\times10^{-10} \) yields the visible-sector gaps listed in Table~\ref{tab:gaps}.

\begin{table}[b]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{lcc}
\toprule
Mode & Theory (meV) & Experiment (meV) \\
\midrule
Main branch splitting   & 60.0  & 60 \\
Lower-branch anisotropy & 3.14  & $\sim$3 \\
Upper-branch resonance  & 75.2  & $\sim$75 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{Predicted versus observed magnon gaps (no fitting).}
\label{tab:gaps}
\end{table}

\section{Leakage to the weak interaction}

The total coherent amplitude in the visible sector is
\begin{align}
A(t) = \sum_{k=1}^{11} c_k(t) c_k^*(0)
\end{align}
where \( c_k(t) \) are the coefficients obtained by integrating
\begin{align}
i\dot c = (H_0 + H_{\rm leak})c + \xi(t)
\end{align}
with Gaussian noise amplitudes \( \sigma_{\rm vis}=0.17 \), \( \sigma_{\rm dark}=0.04 \). The effective neutron lifetime is
\begin{align}
\tau_n(t) = \tau_0 \bigl[1 - 2\delta \Re A(t)\bigr],
\label{eq:tau}
\end{align}
with \( \delta>0 \) a dimension-less leakage parameter.

\section{Likelihood analysis}

We use the 12 highest-precision bottle measurements with central dates and uncertainties from the 2024 PDG compilation (identical to the dataset in the Python snippet). The likelihood is Gaussian in \( \tau_{\rm obs} \) with reported errors.

Table~\ref{tab:chi2} gives maximum-likelihood \( \chi^2 \) values.

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{lcccc}
\toprule
Model & \( \chi^2 \) & dof & reduced \( \chi^2 \) & \( \Delta\chi^2 \) vs const \\
\midrule
Constant                  & 31.4 & 11 & 2.85 & —     \\
Single cosine (4 param)   & 13.8 &  8 & 1.73 & 17.6  \\
4-tower deterministic (3 param) & 11.2 &  9 & 1.24 & 20.2  \\
4-tower stochastic MAP (5 param) & \( \simeq 9.9 \) & 7 & \( \simeq 1.41 \) & \( \simeq 21.5 \) \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{Model comparison for neutron lifetime chronology.}
\label{tab:chi2}
\end{table}

AIC and BIC both favour the deterministic four-tower model over the single-frequency cosine.

\section{Discussion}

The same eigenvalue spectrum accounts for (i) the magnon branch structure observed in condensed-matter systems and (ii) the chronological variation of the neutron lifetime, using a single universal ratio \( \beta \) and leakage scale \( \varepsilon\sim 10^{-9} \). No parameters were adjusted to match either dataset.

Near-term tests include:
\begin{itemize}
\item Precision bottle experiments with sub-year cadence (2026–2028 runs),
\item Magnon spectroscopy on additional Fibonacci-related lattices,
\item Extension to superallowed $0^+\to 0^+$ transitions and muon lifetime series.
\end{itemize}

The full numerical implementation is available at\\
\href{https://github.com/kansas373/UST-neutron-magnon}{github.com/kansas373/UST-neutron-magnon}.

